314","1303":"1303","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","1342":"1342","about 1335":"about 1335","1309":"1309","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Bromley, Kent, England":"Bromley, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Manning","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Cork and Kerry): adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Mainnín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Mainnín</i>’, probably an assimilated form of <i>Mainchín</i>, a diminutive of <i>manach</i> ‘monk’. This is the name of a chieftain family in Connacht. It is sometimes pronounced <i>Ó Maingín</i> and Anglicized as   Mangan  .","English: from a Middle English survival of the Old English personal name <i>Manning</i>.","North German and Dutch: habitational name from a farm so named, once in possession of a certain <i>Manno</i> (see   Mann   2) and his kin."],"variants":[{"name":"Mannen","meanings":["Altered form of Irish or English   Manning  ."]},{"name":"Mannion","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Malachy, Brendan, Aislinn, Brigid, Ciaran, Declan, Dermot, Kieran, Liam, Maeve, Siobhan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mainnín</b> (see   Manning  ).","English and Irish: variant of   Mangan  ."]},{"name":"Mangan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ciaran, Declan.","Irish: from <b>Ó Maingín</b>, see   Mannion  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mongáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Mongán</i>’, a byname for someone with a luxuriant head of hair (from <i>mong</i> ‘hair, mane’)."]},{"name":"Mannings","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Donovan, Eamonn, Ronan.","Irish: variant of   Manning   1, with the addition of English excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":6,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":19,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":28,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Manning was born about 1309, in Bromley, Kent, England as the son of Stephen Manning. He married Joan Chyrfold about 1343. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1342, at the age of 34."},"et":{"about 1309–1342":"umbes 1309–1342","1303–Male":"1303–Surnud","1309–1342":"1309–1342","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1314–1347":"1314–1347","1335–1392":"1335–1392","1270–1309":"1270–1309","1392":"1392","1270":"12